<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br><br>
Put a footnote number in your text to show when you are using another person&#8217;s ideas or words.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	&hellip;help me Brobi Wan Balone.<sup>1</sup>
</blockquote>
<br>
This number directs your reader to a footnote at the bottom of your page. The footnote contains information about the work you are citing, including the author&#8217;s name, details of the work, and relevant page number(s).
<br><br>
<strong>FOOTNOTES</strong>
<br><br>
Footnotes are placed in numerical order at the bottom of the page. In the case of most assignment papers and essays where footnotes and a bibliography are used, the footnote citation details can be quite brief (Example B) because the full details are found in the bibliography. However, if you are instructed by your tutor or lecturer to provide a full reference in the footnote the first time a work is cited, see Example A. If the work is cited again, use the short form (Example B). When there are four or more authors, use the first authorâ€™s name followed by <strong>et al</strong>. (and others).
<br><br>
When shortened references to the same work follow each other with no other references in&#45;between, replace the authors&#8217; names and title with ibid (Example C).
<br>
<br>
<strong>Example A</strong>
<br>
<blockquote class="footnotes ref-indent-1-27cm">
	<span class="smaller">1. Marc Hamilton, et al., <em>Star Warts</em>. Motion picture. Directed by Jeff Lucas (Los Angeles: 20th Century Floss, 1977), Motion picture.</span>
</blockquote>
<br>
<strong>Example B</strong>
<br>
<blockquote class="footnotes ref-indent-1-27cm">
	<span class="smaller">7. Lucas, <em>Star Warts</em>.</span>
</blockquote>
<br>
<strong>Example C</strong>
<br>
<blockquote class="footnotes ref-indent-1-27cm">
	<span class="smaller">8. Ibid.</span>
</blockquote>
